lization of commerce, crime, and political extremism to the impact of climate change on the economy and environment. The reaction from Canada’s policymakers, at least so far, has been underwhelming.In The World Won’t Wait, some of Canada’s brightest thinkers respond. Covering both classic foreign policy issues such as international security, human rights, and global institutions and emerging issues like internet governance, climate change, and sustainable development, their essays offer fresh and provocative responses to today’s challenges and opportunities. The proposals are striking and the contributors diverse: Toronto’s chief city planner makes the case that Canada needs a global urban agenda, while a prominent mining executive explains how to revitalize the country’s position as a world leader in the sector. Their essays are sure to spark the kind of debate that Canada requires if its international policy is to evolve into the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / Sustainable Development.2bisacsh1 aElgie, Sewart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldfarb, Danielle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeesmaat, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeach, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMandel-Campbell, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcArthur, John W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen, Taylor , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOwen, Taylor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaddon, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaquin, Jona